mutant: m046_segment_block_fsync_deleted
target: segment/writer.go
failure-mode: |
  flushLocked writes an active-segment block but skips the file fsync before
  returning success. The ingest writer can then commit seq/next and the relay
  cursor to Pebble while the covering segment bytes exist only in volatile
  cache, so a power loss can recover a durable cursor that points past missing
  archive data.
expected-detection: |
  Killed by the powerloss tier. TestStrictMemDropsUnsyncedFlushedBlock and
  TestWriterStrictMemPowerLossDropsUnsyncedSegmentAndStoreState reset Pebble's
  strict in-memory FS to its synced state and require only fsynced blocks to
  survive. The oracle durable-order checker also observes a segment data write
  followed by a seq/next commit with no intervening segment file sync.
expected-tier: powerloss
tiers: powerloss,default

diff --git a/segment/writer.go b/segment/writer.go
index d783e9f..7e8bb88 100644
--- a/segment/writer.go
+++ b/segment/writer.go
@@ -565,10 +565,6 @@ func (w *Writer) flushLocked() error {
 		w.stickyErr = fmt.Errorf("segment: fsync block: %w", err)
 		return w.stickyErr
 	}
-	if err := syncSegmentFile(w.cfg.FS, w.file); err != nil {
-		w.stickyErr = fmt.Errorf("segment: fsync block: %w", err)
-		return w.stickyErr
-	}
 	return nil
 }
 
